frameDefinitions: An Agent disables a flying or floating Patient, causing it to be unable to support itself in its current medium.
An Agent suddenly and often violently separates the Whole_patient into two or more smaller Pieces, resulting in the Whole_patient no longer existing as such.
The words in this frame describe situations in which an Agent or a Cause injures a Victim.
An Agent finishes an Activity, which can no longer logically continue.
An Agent causes a Firearm to discharge which induces the rapid motion of the Projectile.
frameExamples: It's rumored that she <t>downed</t> a helicopter with a precisely fired arrow.
He <t>ripped</t> <t>up</t> the letter faster than you can say 'Jack Robbins'. INI
Rod saw his father <t>beating</t> his mother.
Jason <t>completed</t> grading the papers late Sunday night.
The bank robber <t>shot</t> at the clerks with an AK-47.
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Agent</fen> forces the <fen>Patient</fen> to come to the ground.
The <fen>Patient</fen> is the entity that is being forced to the ground.
An event which causes the <fen>Patient</fen> to come to the ground.
The time at which the event takes place.
The location at which the event takes place.
The conscious entity, generally a person, that performs the intentional action that results in the <fen>Whole_patient</fen> being broken into <fen>Pieces</fen>.
The entity which is destroyed by the <fen>Agent</fen> and that ends up broken into <fen>Pieces</fen>.
The fragments of the <fen>Whole_patient</fen> that result from the <fen>Agent</fen>'s action.
An event which leads to the fragmentation of the <fen>Whole_patient</fen>.
This role identifies the time when the <fen>Agent</fen> breaks up the <fen>Whole_patient</fen>.
This role identifies the place where the <fen>Agent</fen> breaks the <fen>Whole_patient</fen> into pieces.
<fen>Agent</fen> is the person causing the <fen>Victim</fen>'s injury.

The <fen>Victim</fen> is the being or entity that is injured.  If the <fen>Victim</fen> is included in the phrase indicating <fen>Body_part</fen>, the <fen>Victim</fen> role is tagged on a second role layer (see 3rd example).
The <fen>Body_part</fen> identifies the location on the body where the bodily injury takes place.
The <fen>Cause</fen> marks expressions that indicate some non-intentional, typically non-human, force that inflicts harm on the <fen>Victim</fen>
<fen>Time</fen> identifies the time when the harm-causing event occurs.
<fen>Place</fen> identifies the place where the harm causing event occurs.
This role identifies the <fen>Agent</fen> who has finished an <fen>Activity</fen>.
This role identifies the <fen>Activity</fen> that the <fen>Agent</fen> has finished.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Activity</fen> finishes.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the <fen>Agent</fen> finishes the <fen>Activity</fen>.
The entity whose rapid, dangerous motion is caused by the Agent and/or Firearm.
The Agent is the person performing the intentional act causing the motion of the Projectile.
The <fen>Time</fen> when the shooting event takes place.
The location in which the shooting event takes place.
